 Oberon-2 compiler options
\par }\pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 Compiler options can be changed in the {\i Options/Compiler} dialogue, the settings are stored in the project definition files.
\par \pard \s24 
\par \pard \s24 
Additional code is generated for most options, which results in larger programs and a (small) decrease of program execution speed. Therefore, one should enable the options during development of an application an turn them off for generation of a distribut
ion version. Since the compiler settings incluence the generated code, the program should be carefully checked another time after changing compiler options!
\par \pard \s24 
\par {\b Available Options:
\par 
\par }{\i Debug Symbols
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 The compiler includes linenumber information in the generated code which can be evaluated with the FindError-tool.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i Overflow Check
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 Each numeric operation is checked for overflow condition.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i Type Check
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 The dynamic type of object will be checked at assignments and type guards.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i Index Check
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 The values of array indices are checked against the size of the array.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i Nil Check
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 At run-time is checked, if a referenced pointer is NIL.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i Range Check
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 In every assignment it is checked, whether the value fits into the target variable.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i Initialize Pointers
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 All pointers will be initialized as 0 (NIL).
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 {\i 
\par }\pard \s24 {\i ASSERT Evaluation
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 Code for the evaluation of ASSERT statements is generated. The program will be halted if an assertion fails.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 {\i Smart Callbacks
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 The compiler is forced to generate code, which allows other processes (like the kernel) calls to exported procedures without export declaration in the linker options dialog.
\par \pard \s15\li360\ri360 It is also necessary for object oriented programs, which use classes inside DLLs (like programs written for OPAL or our new object oriented library OPAL++).
\par \pard \s15\li360\ri360 This option is enabled as default.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 Every time one of the above condition fails, then the program stops and the error position (module name and line number) is presented.
