\par }\pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 It is the duty of the linker to combine all modules of a project to one executable file (or dynamic link library). Linker options can be changed in the {\i Options/Linker} dialogue, the settings are stored in the project definition files.

\par \pard \s24 
\par {\b Available Options:
\par }
\par {\i Add, Del
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 This 
buttons insert/delete procedure names to/from the export list. Every Windows callback function (Oberon functions, which shall be called from Windows API functions) must be included in this list! Applications, which make use of Opal's exit-procedures, must
 include the symbol ExitProcThunk!
\par \pard \s15\li360\ri360 The names of exported procedures are put in the non-resident name table as default. If you want to put a name in the resident name table, then add a \ldblquote *\rdblquote  at the end of the symbol name (i.e. \ldblquote 
ExitProcThunk*\rdblquote )
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 {\i Generate DLL
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 The linker generates a DLL instead of an EXE-file.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 {\i Ignore Case
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 The linker does not differ between small and capital letters. This option must be on for Windows programs!
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 {\i DLL runtime-system
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 Generated applications share a common runtime-sytem DLL (rtsobero.dll).\line Advantages: programs get smaller and one can change the runtime-system without new compilation and linkage of the application.\line 
Disadvantage: one has to copy executable file and runtime-system DLL to spread an application.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 {\i Stack size
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 Size of the stack in bytes for the application. DLL's have no own stack, so this option is of no influence for DLL's.
\par \pard\plain \s24 \f2\fs20 
\par \pard \s24 {\i Heap size
\par }\pard\plain \s15\li360\ri360 \f2\fs20 Size of the local heap for the application. The Oberon-2 command NEW does not allocate memory from local heap, therefore this option must not be increased except you explicitely call the Windows function LocalAlloc.

